[1
Date: Sat 20 Oct 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: South Florida Sun Sentinel, Sat 20 Oct 2001 [edited
<http://www.sunsentinel.com/news/yahoo/sfl-pwnile20oct20.story?coll=sf
la%2Dhome%2Dheadlines>

First Equine Case of West Nile Virus Reported in Palm Beach County
--------------------------------------------------
An infection of West Nile virus, the first case in Palm Beach County,
was confirmed on Fri 19 Oct 2001 in a horse in Royal Palm Beach, the
county Health Department said.
As of Fri 19 Oct 2001, sentinel flocks of chickens located throughout
the county continued to test negative for the virus, officials said.
Nevertheless, the Royal Palm Beach case confirms that the virus has
entered the county, health officials said.
Statewide, 11 human cases of West Nile virus have been reported this
year, and 49 of Florida's 67 counties remain under a medical alert for
heightened awareness for the disease's presence, according to the
state Department of Health.
In St. Lucie County, 6 chickens have tested positive in a preliminary
examination for the virus that can cause both the St. Louis and West
Nile illnesses, health officials said on Fri 19 Oct 2001. Additional
tests are being conducted. [This is interpreted to mean that in
preliminary tests the 6 sentinel birds have tested positive for
flavivirus antigen, suggesting that they may have been infected by
either St Louis encephalitis virus or
West Nile virus, related but distinguishable viruses that are
associated with similar but distinguishable illnesses. - Mod.CP
