[2
Date: Wed 24 Oct 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Virginia Department of Agriculture and Consumer Services,
press
release, Tue 23 Oct 2001 [edited
<http://www.vdacs.state.va.us/news/releases-b/102301wnv.html>

Third Horse with West Nile Virus Reported in Virginia
-----------------------------------------------------
A serology (blood) sample from a horse in the Suffolk area has tested
positive for West Nile virus (WNV). The Virginia Department of
Agriculture and Consumer Services (VDACS) submitted the sample for
testing to the Division of Consolidated Laboratories (DCLS) in
Richmond. After a strong positive there, officials sent the sample to
the USDA National Veterinary Services Laboratory in Ames, Iowa.
Because of the number of West Nile cases submitted for testing, VDACS
does not expect final confirmation for another week to 10 days but
says the presumptive positive from DCLS warrants a warning to the
public to protect their horses from mosquitoes, which transmit the
disease.
This is the third case of WNV in a horse in Virginia. The first 2 were
reported in September 2001. The 8-year-old horse, which appears to be
recovering from the infection, is from Suffolk, an area that often has
annual outbreaks of another mosquito-borne encephalitis virus, Eastern
Equine Encephalitis (EEE) virus. Both WNV and EEE virus are normally
maintained in the wild in birds and transferred from birds to animals
and humans by mosquitoes. A number of other diseases, among them
rabies, moldy corn poisoning, and equine protozoal myelitis, can
produce similar symptoms. Animal owners should consult their
veterinarians or the nearest VDACS Regional Animal Health Laboratory
if an animal exhibits any neurologic symptoms such as a stumbling
gait, facial paralysis, drooping, or disinterest in the surroundings.
